ECG Signal-Based Stress Classification using Machine Learning
Overview

This project focuses on analyzing Electrocardiogram (ECG) signals to classify stress levels using machine learning techniques. The goal is to explore how physiological signals can be processed and interpreted to identify stress patterns in a reliable and automated way.

The system combines signal processing methods with machine learning models to extract meaningful insights from raw ECG data and perform classification based on learned patterns.

Objectives
To understand ECG signal characteristics and their relation to stress
To preprocess raw ECG signals for noise removal
To extract meaningful features from the signals
To build a machine learning model for stress classification
To evaluate the performance of the model
Methodology
1. Data Acquisition

ECG signal data was collected from available datasets / simulated sources for analysis.

2. Signal Preprocessing
Removal of noise and unwanted artifacts
Filtering to improve signal quality
Normalization for consistent input
3. Feature Extraction

Key features were extracted to represent the ECG signals effectively:

Heart Rate Variability (HRV)
Time-domain features
Frequency-domain features
4. Model Development

A machine learning model was developed to classify stress levels based on extracted features. The model learns patterns from the data and predicts stress categories.

5. Evaluation

The model performance was evaluated using standard metrics to assess classification effectiveness.

